Introduction¶

In this project, we will be analysing dataset associated with how many patients show up to the doctors after making an appointment. In particular, we will be finding trends among patients who show up timely on appointments and how they differ from those who do not show up.

The original dataset has been sourced from Kaggle Dataset: Medical Appointment No Shows on 29th October 2018.

"No-show Appointments" is a dataset that collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

It includes the following columns:

1- PatientId- Identification of a patient

2- AppointmentID- Identification of each appointment

3- Gender- Male or Female

4- ScheduleDay- What day the patient set up their appointment.

5- AppointmentDay- The day of the actual appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.

6- Age- How old is the patient

7- Neighbourhood- Location of the hospital

8- Scholarship- Whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia.

9- Hipertension- True or False

10- Diabetes- True or False

11- Alcoholism- True or False

12- Handcap- 4 types of conditions

13-SMS_received- 1 or more messages sent to the patient

14- No-show- Yes is patient showed up and No if not.

The most interesting question here is that what factors are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?

Another question to investigate is whether the waiting time (difference between the day appointment was scheduled and when it actually was) impacted the chances of people showing up?

Data Cleaning¶

Clean the data, make any changes required in the data:

1-Rename column names to lowercase,correct misspelled ones (handcap, hipertension), remove any underscores or dashes ( no-show, sms_received).

2- Remove age<0 and age>100

3- Remove handicap = 2,3,4

4- Remove unwanted columns (patiendId, appointmentId)

5- Change data type of scheduledday and appointment day to datetime from object.

6- Change No-show column from object to int; 'No' to 0 and 'Yes' to 1

7- Add a new column, 'weekday' according to the appointment day.

Research Question 1¶

What factors are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?

We will address this question by computing statistics and creating visualisations. Look at various independent variables, one at a time and see how it effects the dependent variable (noshow).

In [0]:
#Plot the Count Plot
def plotCountPlot(feature, hue,title,labels):
  ax = sns.countplot(x=feature,hue=hue, data=df)
  ax.set_title(title)
  x_ticks_labels=labels
  ax.set_xticklabels(x_ticks_labels)
  plt.show()
In [0]:
#Plot the bar plot
def plotBar(x,title):
  ax = sns.barplot(x=x.index, y=x)
  ax.set_title(title)
  ax.set_ylabel('Percentage')

This shows that more females showed up than males but to confirm this and see if the gender has an effect on the results, we need to compare the proportion of females and males that showed up.

In [228]:
#Divide the ages into various age groups and create a new column, 'agegroup'
conditions = [
    (df['age'] <1),
    (df['age'] >0 ) & (df.age < 13),
    (df.age >12)& (df.age<20),
    (df.age>19)& (df.age<65),
    (df.age>64)
    ]
groups = ['infants', 'children', 'teen','adults','elderly']

#Create new column, 'agegroup' for these categories
df['agegroup'] = np.select(conditions, groups, default='black')
df.agegroup.value_counts()

#Find percentage of patients in each age group that showed up
df_agegroup_ratio= df[df.noshow == 0].groupby(['agegroup']).size()/df.groupby(['agegroup']).size()*100
print(df_agegroup_ratio)

#Plot the results
plotBar(df_agegroup_ratio,"Percentage of patients that Show Up by Age groups")

agegroup
adults      79.688524
children    79.038627
elderly     84.570312
infants     81.944052
teen        73.980956
dtype: float64

This graph gives a clearer picture of the results as we can now see that teens have the least probability of showing up (around 74%) as compared to all the other age groups.

Elderly(around 84%) had the most probability, then infants (around 82%), then adults (around 80%), then children (around 79%) and last teens(around 74%).

So depending on the age group, we can predict the chances of the patient showing up.

Multiple variable (2d) explorations

In [0]:
#Function to find and plot graph to investigate effect of multiple variables on percentage of people showing up 
def show_gender_variable(variable,v):
  #find percentage of patients who show up based on gender and any other independent variable
  ratio= df[df.noshow == 0].groupby([v,variable])['noshow'].count()/df.groupby([v,variable])['noshow'].count()*100

  #Plot the results
  ratio.unstack(v).plot.bar().set_ylabel('percentage')
In [254]:
# Apply function show_gender_variable() for each age group to column names 'diabetes','hypertension','alcoholism', 'smsreceived','scholarship' 
df.apply(lambda x: show_gender_variable(x,'agegroup') if x.name in ['diabetes','hypertension','alcoholism', 'smsreceived','scholarship','handicap'] else None);

In each case, Elderly showed up most and teens showed up the least except for in handicap conditions.

Generally males tend to show up more than females except in case of teens and children

Research Question 2¶

Will waiting time (difference between the day appointment was scheduled and when it actually was) impact the chances of people showing up?

We will address this question by computing difference between the two variables(scheduled day and appointment day) and then seeing its trend with no show variable through graph.

Most patients showed up when the appointment was on the same day as scheduled

Conclusions¶

My analysis revealed that:

Patients with the states diseases (hypertension, diabetes, handicapped) showed up more as compared to those without the diseases.

Alcoholism didnot effect the chances of patients showing up.

Waiting time greatly impacted the percentage of people showing up or not. As the difference between the scheduled day and appointment day decreased, more number of patients showed up. Most showed up when appointment was on the same day as scheduled.

Elderly people showed up the most among age groups.

People upon not receiving the sms showed up more than those receiving.

People without the scholarship showed up more.

Gender has no influence on proportion of shows/no-shows.

Limitations¶

The analysis is limited to visualisation through graphs;only seeing the trends and value distributions. Since no statistical tests have been performed, we cannot draw any causations.
